---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import DownloadCta from "../components/DownloadCta.astro";
import { withBase } from "../config.mjs";
import { positioning } from "../data/app.mjs";
---

<Base
  title="KaiZenly+ vs Blockit & Timer Lock Apps — Blockit Alternative for Android"
  path="/compare/"
  description="Blockit alternative for Android. KaiZenly+ goes beyond timer-based blocking with allowed-apps list, scheduled focus, bedtime mode, habit tracker, journaling & mood tracking."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:860px">
      <span class="eyebrow">Blockit alternative · Comparison</span>
      <h1 class="display-lg" style="margin-top:10px">KaiZenly+ vs Blockit &amp; timer-based app blockers</h1>
      <p class="lede" style="margin-top:16px">
        Many popular focus apps — such as Blockit — do one core thing: you set a timer and the phone
        stays locked until it ends, with one emergency exit. That helps in the moment, but it does not
        build a routine. KaiZenly+ does the very same timed lock and emergency exit, then adds the rest
        of the system around it, so a single app covers both <strong>protecting</strong> your focus and
        <strong>improving</strong> your daily life.
      </p>
      <p class="secondary" style="margin-top:12px">
        {positioning.notJustABlocker}
      </p>
      <div class="card" style="margin-top:20px;border-left:3px solid var(--ink)">
        <h2 style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:1.05rem">It does the core blocking too — then goes further</h2>
        <p style="margin:0">{positioning.coreParity}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:920px">
      <div class="cmp-table-wrap">
        <table class="cmp-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">What you compare</th>
              <th scope="col">Timer-based lock apps (e.g. Blockit)</th>
              <th scope="col" class="cmp-kz">KaiZenly+</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {positioning.vsSimpleLockApps.map((r) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{r.point}</td>
                <td class="cmp-other">{r.simpleLock}</td>
                <td class="cmp-kz">{r.kaizenly}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="note" style="margin-top:16px">
        Timer-based lock apps such as Blockit do the core job well — you set a session length and the
        phone stays locked until it ends, with an emergency exit. KaiZenly+ matches that core and adds
        an allowed-apps list, schedules, bedtime mode, habits, journaling, mood, and insights around it.
        App features change over time, so always check the current details of any app you are comparing.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:860px">
      <div class="section-head"><h2 class="display-md">Where KaiZenly+ goes further</h2></div>
      <ul class="feature-list">
        {positioning.advantages.map((a) => (<li>{a}</li>))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" style="background:var(--surface);border-block:1px solid var(--hairline)">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:860px">
      <div class="section-head"><h2 class="display-md">The point most blockers miss</h2></div>
      <div class="grid grid-2">
        <article class="card">
          <h3>You should not have to fully lock your phone</h3>
          <p>
            Real life needs calls, maps, notes, study tools, work apps, and the occasional emergency
            app. KaiZenly+ lets you keep an <strong>allowed-apps list of up to 8 essential apps</strong>
            usable during focus, while everything distracting stays blocked. That is more practical
            than an all-or-nothing lock.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <h3>Focus should build a routine, not just pause the phone</h3>
          <p>
            A timer that locks the screen helps once. KaiZenly+ adds <strong>scheduled focus</strong>,
            a <strong>bedtime mode</strong>, <strong>habits</strong>, <strong>journaling</strong>,
            <strong>mood tracking</strong>, and <strong>insights</strong> — so each focus session
            feeds a longer-term routine instead of being a one-off.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="container center" style="max-width:640px">
      <h2 class="display-md">A blocker and a routine system in one</h2>
      <p class="lede" style="margin-top:14px">
        Free at launch, coming soon to Google Play — with everything kept on your own device.
      </p>
      <div class="btn-row" style="justify-content:center;margin-top:24px">
        <DownloadCta size="lg" />
        <a class="btn btn-secondary btn-lg" href={withBase("/zen-shield/")}>How Zen Shield works</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
